# 🚀 Introduction to API (Application Programming Interface)

|| 📘 What is an API? ||

An API (Application Programming Interface) is a set of rules that allows two software applications to communicate with each other.  
It acts as a bridge between the frontend (client) and the backend (server).

---

|| 🍽️ Real-life Example ||

Imagine a **waiter** in a restaurant. The waiter takes your order (request), goes to the kitchen (server), brings your food (response), and gives it to you.  
Similarly, an API handles communication between your app and the server.

---

|| ⚙️ How Does an API Work? ||

1. The Client sends a request to the API.
2. The API forwards the request to the Server.
3. The Server sends back a Response.
4. The API delivers the response to the Client.

---

|| 🧰 Common Types of APIs ||

- REST API – Uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, etc.) – Most widely used.
- SOAP API – XML-based and more secure, but complex.
- GraphQL – Used for more dynamic and flexible queries.

---

|| 🔑 Common HTTP Methods ||

| Method  | Description                  |
|---------|------------------------------|
| GET     | Retrieve data                |
| POST    | Send new data                |
| PUT     | Update existing data         |
| DELETE  | Delete data                  |

---

|| 🧪 Example API Call (Using Fetch) ||

```javascript
fetch('https://api.example.com/users')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data));

